WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:07.322 --> 00:00:09.030
MALE SPEAKER: Good
afternoon, and welcome

00:00:09.030 --> 00:00:11.470
to Talks at Google
in Cambridge, Mass.

00:00:11.470 --> 00:00:15.230
Today it's my great pleasure to
introduce Josh Glenn and Tony

00:00:15.230 --> 00:00:19.400
Leone, one of the co-authors
and the designer, respectively,

00:00:19.400 --> 00:00:22.400
of the "Unbored"
series of books.

00:00:22.400 --> 00:00:25.860
Along with co-author
Elizabeth Foy Larson,

00:00:25.860 --> 00:00:28.820
Josh and Tony are on a
mission to empower kids

00:00:28.820 --> 00:00:30.825
to appreciate all
the world can offer

00:00:30.825 --> 00:00:35.340
and to help them see how they
can add their own magic to it.

00:00:35.340 --> 00:00:38.500
Their first book, "Unbored:
The Essential Field Guide

00:00:38.500 --> 00:00:42.660
to Serious Fun," has been
described as "the first kids'

00:00:42.660 --> 00:00:46.520
book to truly encourage a
hands-on approach to creating

00:00:46.520 --> 00:00:48.830
a personally meaningful life."

00:00:48.830 --> 00:00:52.140
Their third book will
be "Unbored Adventure."

00:00:52.140 --> 00:00:54.660
But today they're here to talk
about their newly published

00:00:54.660 --> 00:00:59.670
second book, "Unbored Games:
Serious Fun for Everyone."

00:00:59.670 --> 00:01:02.490
I can't adequately
describe how amazing it is.

00:01:02.490 --> 00:01:03.570
I've read it.

00:01:03.570 --> 00:01:07.940
So I'll just say I wish I'd had
it when I was a kid, and had it

00:01:07.940 --> 00:01:09.610
when my kids were young.

00:01:09.610 --> 00:01:11.950
So please join me in
welcoming Josh and Tony.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:19.980
JOSH GLENN: Thank you.

00:01:19.980 --> 00:01:22.110
I'll let you drive the
machine, I guess, Tony.

00:01:22.110 --> 00:01:24.190
TONY LEONE: Sure.

00:01:24.190 --> 00:01:26.430
JOSH GLENN: So I'm Josh Glenn.

00:01:26.430 --> 00:01:31.670
I'm born and raised here in
Boston, in Jamaica Plain.

00:01:31.670 --> 00:01:33.470
Are you from Jamaica Plain?

00:01:33.470 --> 00:01:34.480
Nice.

00:01:34.480 --> 00:01:38.980
I'm from Parkside, not Pondside.

00:01:38.980 --> 00:01:44.022
And I'm a semiotic brand
analyst in my real life.

00:01:44.022 --> 00:01:46.230
I used to work at "The Boston
Globe" for a long time.

00:01:46.230 --> 00:01:47.980
I was a columnist and
editor for the Ideas

00:01:47.980 --> 00:01:50.300
section for a long time.

00:01:50.300 --> 00:01:51.515
And Tony?

00:01:51.515 --> 00:01:52.640
TONY LEONE: I'm Tony Leone.

00:01:52.640 --> 00:01:56.000
I'm a graphic designer
here in the Boston area,

00:01:56.000 --> 00:01:57.470
working-- I went to Mass Art.

00:01:57.470 --> 00:01:59.650
I graduated from
Mass Art in '95,

00:01:59.650 --> 00:02:02.345
have been working in
Boston ever since.

00:02:02.345 --> 00:02:04.720
I've done a lot of work over
the years, about seven years

00:02:04.720 --> 00:02:05.790
worth of work, with Ideo.

00:02:05.790 --> 00:02:08.690
They're over in Central Square.

00:02:08.690 --> 00:02:11.290
But for the past eight years
or so I've been out on my own,

00:02:11.290 --> 00:02:13.460
running my own studio
and happily working

00:02:13.460 --> 00:02:15.270
on the "Unbored"
books with Josh.

00:02:15.270 --> 00:02:17.957
So I'm a more
traditional designer.

00:02:17.957 --> 00:02:19.540
I'm not so much of
a web guy, but more

00:02:19.540 --> 00:02:25.771
of a packaging, publications,
books, and brand designer.

00:02:25.771 --> 00:02:28.020
JOSH GLENN: So we're going
to talk to you a little bit

00:02:28.020 --> 00:02:30.040
about our creative process,
actually, here today.

00:02:30.040 --> 00:02:31.900
But then we'll also talk
about our games book,

00:02:31.900 --> 00:02:33.816
and we can even play a
game if you guys want--

00:02:33.816 --> 00:02:35.250
if we don't run out of time.

00:02:35.250 --> 00:02:37.880
But first we're going to talk
a little bit about-- just

00:02:37.880 --> 00:02:40.980
because we're so fascinated
by our own process--

00:02:40.980 --> 00:02:43.780
our process of how we made this
first book, "Unbored," which

00:02:43.780 --> 00:02:48.840
was a bestseller back in 2012.

00:02:48.840 --> 00:02:52.670
TONY LEONE: Josh and I, we
met back in the late '90s,

00:02:52.670 --> 00:02:56.440
and Josh was running a zine
called "Hermenaut" at the time.

00:02:56.440 --> 00:03:00.290
I got to know Josh because he
hired me as the art director

00:03:00.290 --> 00:03:04.490
and designer of Issues
15 and 16 of the zine.

00:03:04.490 --> 00:03:05.950
And what we
essentially did was we

00:03:05.950 --> 00:03:08.180
took something that
was in a zine format

00:03:08.180 --> 00:03:11.510
and created more of
a journal with it.

00:03:11.510 --> 00:03:14.060
So Josh I do have a history
of working together,

00:03:14.060 --> 00:03:17.400
and especially working
together collaboratively

00:03:17.400 --> 00:03:18.880
on large publication projects.

00:03:18.880 --> 00:03:20.660
We did two issues
of "Hermenaut."

00:03:20.660 --> 00:03:22.970
And so we're just giving you
a little bit of background

00:03:22.970 --> 00:03:23.470
as to--

00:03:23.470 --> 00:03:26.780
JOSH GLENN: And of course,
the zine world, we were DIY.

00:03:26.780 --> 00:03:29.230
But the ethos, the
aesthetic was supposed

00:03:29.230 --> 00:03:31.855
to be very-- it wasn't
cool to have things that

00:03:31.855 --> 00:03:35.600
were glossy and color covers
and nice layout and all that.

00:03:35.600 --> 00:03:37.730
Tony and I were like,
that's not DIY at all.

00:03:37.730 --> 00:03:40.165
DIY is just, if you
make it yourself

00:03:40.165 --> 00:03:42.290
and no one's telling you
what to do, then it's DIY.

00:03:42.290 --> 00:03:43.873
You can have it look
however you want.

00:03:43.873 --> 00:03:45.730
So we took-- although
the zine started

00:03:45.730 --> 00:03:48.730
as kind of a mimeographed
thing for 20 people,

00:03:48.730 --> 00:03:51.256
we turned it into this
very beautiful journal that

00:03:51.256 --> 00:03:58.300
had a circulation of
10,000 before the end.

00:03:58.300 --> 00:04:00.380
TONY LEONE: So in
spring of 2010,

00:04:00.380 --> 00:04:04.590
we pitched the book "Unbored."

00:04:04.590 --> 00:04:07.270
And the idea was that it
was the best of the old

00:04:07.270 --> 00:04:08.320
and the best of the new.

00:04:08.320 --> 00:04:09.986
Josh, I'll let you
take this part of it.

00:04:09.986 --> 00:04:12.330
JOSH GLENN: Yeah, so
there was this book that

00:04:12.330 --> 00:04:14.580
was very popular around that
time, "The Dangerous Book

00:04:14.580 --> 00:04:17.029
for Boys" that was
very nostalgic.

00:04:17.029 --> 00:04:19.820
And I had-- my kids
at that time were--

00:04:19.820 --> 00:04:21.755
my two sons were age 12 and 10.

00:04:21.755 --> 00:04:23.130
And they had been
given, I think,

00:04:23.130 --> 00:04:25.260
three copies of that
book by usually,

00:04:25.260 --> 00:04:26.890
like, grandparents
or aunts or uncles,

00:04:26.890 --> 00:04:28.390
or other people who were
kind of worried about how

00:04:28.390 --> 00:04:29.490
kids are growing up these days.

00:04:29.490 --> 00:04:31.448
They felt like, supposedly
kids these days they

00:04:31.448 --> 00:04:33.539
spend all their time on
TV or on screens or video

00:04:33.539 --> 00:04:35.330
games, the Internet,
they don't go outside.

00:04:35.330 --> 00:04:36.710
Parents overparent
and they're worried

00:04:36.710 --> 00:04:38.501
about letting their
kids run around outside

00:04:38.501 --> 00:04:39.560
and be in the woods.

00:04:39.560 --> 00:04:41.810
And there was a lot of
nostalgia for the good old days

00:04:41.810 --> 00:04:42.460
of childhood.

00:04:42.460 --> 00:04:44.710
So "The Dangerous Book for
Boys" was a huge publishing

00:04:44.710 --> 00:04:45.960
phenomenon.

00:04:45.960 --> 00:04:50.214
And what frustrated me and Tony
and our co-author Elizabeth

00:04:50.214 --> 00:04:52.130
Larson, who couldn't be
here because she lives

00:04:52.130 --> 00:04:55.130
in Minneapolis-- what frustrated
us about books like that

00:04:55.130 --> 00:04:57.405
and a lot of books
that imitate it

00:04:57.405 --> 00:05:00.060
that have come out since
then is that they're just

00:05:00.060 --> 00:05:00.820
a nostalgia trip.

00:05:00.820 --> 00:05:02.745
They're very afraid
of the present, and so

00:05:02.745 --> 00:05:04.203
their reaction to
the present-- not

00:05:04.203 --> 00:05:06.619
that their criticism of the
present is wrong, necessarily,

00:05:06.619 --> 00:05:08.540
but the reaction was to
retreat into the past,

00:05:08.540 --> 00:05:11.410
into this nostalgic idea of
how childhood used to be.

00:05:11.410 --> 00:05:13.880
And we wanted books
for our kids that

00:05:13.880 --> 00:05:16.500
were about now, that
were about-- that

00:05:16.500 --> 00:05:17.440
weren't hypocritical.

00:05:17.440 --> 00:05:18.550
And we use the computer.

00:05:18.550 --> 00:05:19.924
We let our kids
use the computer.

00:05:19.924 --> 00:05:22.830
We like games, video games.

00:05:22.830 --> 00:05:25.350
So we wanted books
that would have

00:05:25.350 --> 00:05:26.930
some of that good
old-fashioned kind

00:05:26.930 --> 00:05:31.624
of outdoor, no-screen,
low-tech activities for kids.

00:05:31.624 --> 00:05:33.040
We wanted it to
be realistic, too,

00:05:33.040 --> 00:05:36.125
and have a book that would
be a way of exploring

00:05:36.125 --> 00:05:37.500
the world together
with our kids.

00:05:37.500 --> 00:05:39.070
And that book
didn't really exist.

00:05:39.070 --> 00:05:41.403
So we pitched this best of
the old, best of the new idea

00:05:41.403 --> 00:05:42.760
to Bloomsbury.

00:05:42.760 --> 00:05:46.440
TONY LEONE: And so in
order to pitch the book,

00:05:46.440 --> 00:05:49.050
Josh wrote a couple
of articles and I

00:05:49.050 --> 00:05:51.610
designed some very
loose, rough spreads

00:05:51.610 --> 00:05:53.310
of what it might look like.

00:05:53.310 --> 00:05:55.240
So we chose the game Foursquare.

00:05:55.240 --> 00:05:57.032
So Josh wrote an article
about Foursquare--

00:05:57.032 --> 00:05:59.115
JOSH GLENN: As an example
of an old-fashioned game

00:05:59.115 --> 00:06:01.077
that doesn't require any
technology or screens.

00:06:01.077 --> 00:06:01.910
TONY LEONE: Exactly.

00:06:01.910 --> 00:06:04.979
And then we did
Foursquare, the app.

00:06:04.979 --> 00:06:07.520
JOSH GLENN: Which my kids and
I used, even though at the time

00:06:07.520 --> 00:06:10.490
it was really sort of a
way for people in their 20s

00:06:10.490 --> 00:06:12.710
to find their friends and
to brag about how many bars

00:06:12.710 --> 00:06:14.460
they'd been to that
night or whatever.

00:06:14.460 --> 00:06:16.210
My kids and I used
Foursquare all the time

00:06:16.210 --> 00:06:19.400
because it was a way to force
us out of our normal routines.

00:06:19.400 --> 00:06:22.030
So if we were in Brookline
and dropping one of my kids

00:06:22.030 --> 00:06:24.510
off at his bass lesson
and my other son

00:06:24.510 --> 00:06:26.780
I had an hour to kill,
we would use Foursquare

00:06:26.780 --> 00:06:28.390
and say, hey, no one
checked into this graveyard.

00:06:28.390 --> 00:06:30.348
Let's go into the graveyard
and check in there.

00:06:30.348 --> 00:06:33.860
So we turned it into a fun way
for me and an eight-year-old

00:06:33.860 --> 00:06:37.310
to spend time together
exploring the world

00:06:37.310 --> 00:06:38.540
and using an app to do it.

00:06:38.540 --> 00:06:40.920
So to us that doesn't
seem like a bad thing.

00:06:40.920 --> 00:06:42.087
It seemed like a good thing.

00:06:42.087 --> 00:06:43.753
TONY LEONE: And just
to say a little bit

00:06:43.753 --> 00:06:46.450
about the design of the spreads,
the editor we were working

00:06:46.450 --> 00:06:49.350
with at Bloomsbury, he
called us pretty much about,

00:06:49.350 --> 00:06:51.724
I would say about two
days before our meeting,

00:06:51.724 --> 00:06:53.140
and he said, oh,
it would be great

00:06:53.140 --> 00:06:55.390
if you had some visuals to
come along with your pitch.

00:06:55.390 --> 00:06:58.570
So we hurriedly
put these together.

00:06:58.570 --> 00:07:01.190
And it really raised
a lot of questions

00:07:01.190 --> 00:07:03.390
as to what this book
should look like.

00:07:03.390 --> 00:07:06.064
And we'll talk a little
more about that in a bit.

00:07:09.940 --> 00:07:11.740
So we pitched the book.

00:07:11.740 --> 00:07:13.750
We got a contract that summer.

00:07:13.750 --> 00:07:17.600
And as I typically start with
any large-scale design project,

00:07:17.600 --> 00:07:21.080
and Josh does in his work,
we did a lot of research.

00:07:21.080 --> 00:07:26.130
I spent a good several weeks
researching the market segment

00:07:26.130 --> 00:07:30.100
of kids and family
activity books.

00:07:30.100 --> 00:07:32.240
And I scoured the
market, and I just

00:07:32.240 --> 00:07:34.700
collected images and
spreads from all the books.

00:07:34.700 --> 00:07:38.110
And very quickly a
series of themes came up.

00:07:38.110 --> 00:07:40.380
So we broke it out
into nostalgic.

00:07:40.380 --> 00:07:42.500
So this is "The
Dangerous Book for Boys,"

00:07:42.500 --> 00:07:45.140
"The Daring Book for Girls,"
the "Field and Forest"--

00:07:45.140 --> 00:07:48.160
the "Handy" books, which
is a pretty famous series.

00:07:48.160 --> 00:07:51.410
Another theme emerged, which
was appropriated or retro.

00:07:51.410 --> 00:07:53.800
So there's the "Popular
Mechanics," you know,

00:07:53.800 --> 00:07:57.190
the boy scientist,
the girl mechanic.

00:07:57.190 --> 00:07:58.910
"The Worst Case
Scenario" handbooks,

00:07:58.910 --> 00:08:01.520
where they're meant to
look like survival guides.

00:08:01.520 --> 00:08:04.310
"The Zombie Survival Guide."

00:08:04.310 --> 00:08:07.401
Another style that
came up was, for lack

00:08:07.401 --> 00:08:09.400
of a better word, a styled
graphic illustration,

00:08:09.400 --> 00:08:11.520
where they were
designed or created

00:08:11.520 --> 00:08:15.760
by designers who are half
designer and half Illustrator,

00:08:15.760 --> 00:08:19.890
and they kind of
created their own look,

00:08:19.890 --> 00:08:23.100
but that had a very
computer-centric sort

00:08:23.100 --> 00:08:25.600
of illustration style.

00:08:25.600 --> 00:08:26.900
Eclectic collage.

00:08:26.900 --> 00:08:28.950
This is very much the
DK books for kids.

00:08:28.950 --> 00:08:33.049
DK Publish has mastered
this look for kids.

00:08:33.049 --> 00:08:35.520
So we knew right away we wanted
to maybe do some of this,

00:08:35.520 --> 00:08:40.110
but we didn't want to be
just another DK type of book.

00:08:40.110 --> 00:08:44.190
Again, they master it, so we
found a lot of that stuff.

00:08:44.190 --> 00:08:46.990
Another feature that came
up was this contemporary,

00:08:46.990 --> 00:08:48.650
what I call
contemporary technical.

00:08:48.650 --> 00:08:51.050
And this is very
much like the, you're

00:08:51.050 --> 00:08:53.550
on a flight in the airplane in
there's sort of the emergency

00:08:53.550 --> 00:08:55.262
exit pamphlet in the airplane.

00:08:55.262 --> 00:08:56.553
It's that type of illustration.

00:08:59.110 --> 00:09:01.750
And then certainly
just modern design,

00:09:01.750 --> 00:09:04.630
things that aren't necessarily
a particular style,

00:09:04.630 --> 00:09:07.360
but just created by designers,
like the ReadyMade books

00:09:07.360 --> 00:09:09.170
and the ReadyMade
magazines, great.

00:09:09.170 --> 00:09:11.170
Ellen Lupton's books
for kids are great.

00:09:13.770 --> 00:09:15.680
And here's a series
more. "The Mini Weapons

00:09:15.680 --> 00:09:17.330
of Mass Destruction"
are great books.

00:09:17.330 --> 00:09:21.570
"Geek Dads," and certainly
"Make" magazine as well.

00:09:21.570 --> 00:09:23.740
And then lastly,
illustrated characters.

00:09:23.740 --> 00:09:26.440
You know, the sort of classic
way to reach out to kids

00:09:26.440 --> 00:09:29.480
is through some sort of
cartoon-like character

00:09:29.480 --> 00:09:30.970
or characters that
sort of run you

00:09:30.970 --> 00:09:34.507
through either a
lesson or an activity.

00:09:34.507 --> 00:09:36.840
Here's some more here. "The
Middle School Confidential."

00:09:36.840 --> 00:09:39.048
And then there's a lot of
stuff like the "Oh, Yikes!"

00:09:39.048 --> 00:09:42.580
books, stuff that's cartoony
or meant to be gross or silly.

00:09:42.580 --> 00:09:46.010
That was another theme
that started to emerge.

00:09:46.010 --> 00:09:49.750
And lastly, these are
illustrated character books,

00:09:49.750 --> 00:09:51.161
but yet they're
more stuff almost

00:09:51.161 --> 00:09:53.410
you would see in your high
school guidance counselor's

00:09:53.410 --> 00:09:55.160
office or a doctor's
office or something.

00:09:55.160 --> 00:09:57.310
You know, "Boy's Guide
to Becoming a Teen."

00:09:57.310 --> 00:10:01.050
We knew right away this is
not where we wanted to be.

00:10:01.050 --> 00:10:03.657
JOSH GLENN: So to be clear,
those are all good books

00:10:03.657 --> 00:10:06.240
that we looked at, and they're
all perfectly good illustration

00:10:06.240 --> 00:10:07.279
styles.

00:10:07.279 --> 00:10:08.820
So our question is,
what do we want--

00:10:08.820 --> 00:10:09.987
what's right for our book?

00:10:09.987 --> 00:10:11.820
And one thing I love
about working with Tony

00:10:11.820 --> 00:10:14.680
is, he and I are both very
left-brained and right-brained.

00:10:14.680 --> 00:10:16.465
So we're very creative
and imaginative,

00:10:16.465 --> 00:10:19.030
but we're also very analytical
and like to do our research.

00:10:19.030 --> 00:10:21.020
In fact, Tony's
wife complains to me

00:10:21.020 --> 00:10:22.815
sometimes that when
they frame a picture

00:10:22.815 --> 00:10:25.106
it takes like six months to
get it hung up on the wall,

00:10:25.106 --> 00:10:29.835
because Tony's like thinking,
planning each wall, studying.

00:10:29.835 --> 00:10:30.890
But I like that.

00:10:30.890 --> 00:10:32.410
So we did a lot of research.

00:10:32.410 --> 00:10:35.230
And then I decided to
use some of the tools I

00:10:35.230 --> 00:10:37.230
use in my work as a
semiotic brand analyst

00:10:37.230 --> 00:10:41.780
to look at the stimulus, the
data that Tony had collected.

00:10:41.780 --> 00:10:45.040
So this is the next
step that we took.

00:10:45.040 --> 00:10:48.870
So what I do in my work
is, I use the tools

00:10:48.870 --> 00:10:53.490
of semiotic analysis to surface
critical insights for marketers

00:10:53.490 --> 00:10:55.260
and branders and
organizations, anybody

00:10:55.260 --> 00:10:57.510
who has a brand that they're
trying to get out there,

00:10:57.510 --> 00:10:59.676
to help them understand the
context in which they're

00:10:59.676 --> 00:11:00.450
operating.

00:11:00.450 --> 00:11:03.040
There's a saying in marketing--
I'm not actually in marketing,

00:11:03.040 --> 00:11:05.620
but I consult to
marketers-- that it doesn't

00:11:05.620 --> 00:11:07.750
matter what your
brand communicates.

00:11:07.750 --> 00:11:10.305
What matters is what
the consumer hears,

00:11:10.305 --> 00:11:12.055
because there's a gap
between what you say

00:11:12.055 --> 00:11:12.880
and what they hear.

00:11:12.880 --> 00:11:14.630
And that gap is
filled with culture.

00:11:14.630 --> 00:11:16.590
There's all this
unspoken network

00:11:16.590 --> 00:11:19.810
of codes and
assumptions and ways

00:11:19.810 --> 00:11:23.540
of thinking that affect
and influence and drive

00:11:23.540 --> 00:11:25.810
our understanding and our
interpretation of everything

00:11:25.810 --> 00:11:29.520
that is sent to us, whether it's
from culture or from marketing.

00:11:29.520 --> 00:11:34.740
So what I do in my work is do a
deep dive into a category, all

00:11:34.740 --> 00:11:37.410
the images and
visuals, whether it's

00:11:37.410 --> 00:11:39.186
the beer category or
automotive, or more

00:11:39.186 --> 00:11:42.490
like a cultural territory
like Britishness or luxury.

00:11:42.490 --> 00:11:45.600
And I surface all these
codes and then map them,

00:11:45.600 --> 00:11:47.660
trying to find the
deep underlying themes

00:11:47.660 --> 00:11:49.210
of that category.

00:11:49.210 --> 00:11:51.900
And then that kind of
becomes a strategic tool

00:11:51.900 --> 00:11:54.660
that I can hand over to the
marketing people or the brand

00:11:54.660 --> 00:11:56.130
stakeholders, and
they can kind of

00:11:56.130 --> 00:11:57.880
have a sense of where
they want to operate

00:11:57.880 --> 00:11:58.969
and how they can operate.

00:11:58.969 --> 00:12:00.510
So I said, well,
why don't I just use

00:12:00.510 --> 00:12:03.700
that same tool for Tony's work?

00:12:03.700 --> 00:12:04.230
So we did.

00:12:04.230 --> 00:12:09.720
So one big, underlying, binary
opposition that we determined

00:12:09.720 --> 00:12:11.795
was in the world of
kids' books at that time

00:12:11.795 --> 00:12:16.530
that we did the study was a big
opposition between silly books

00:12:16.530 --> 00:12:17.320
and earnest books.

00:12:17.320 --> 00:12:18.350
So on the one hand
there was books

00:12:18.350 --> 00:12:20.808
that are very much like for
kids only, like the "Oh, Yuck!"

00:12:20.808 --> 00:12:21.850
type of books, boys only.

00:12:21.850 --> 00:12:23.266
Like parents not
invited basically

00:12:23.266 --> 00:12:24.940
was the message of
these kind of books.

00:12:24.940 --> 00:12:26.200
It's the kind of thing you
would give to your kids

00:12:26.200 --> 00:12:27.760
and hopefully they
would leave you alone

00:12:27.760 --> 00:12:30.176
for a while, which was obviously
not what we wanted to do.

00:12:30.176 --> 00:12:32.870
We wanted a project for kids
that you could do with parents.

00:12:32.870 --> 00:12:34.286
The other end of
that spectrum was

00:12:34.286 --> 00:12:35.920
kind of earnest,
very earnest books

00:12:35.920 --> 00:12:39.590
that were kind of
for parents, and they

00:12:39.590 --> 00:12:44.720
were sort of parenting guides
and not that fun for the kids.

00:12:44.720 --> 00:12:46.770
And somewhere
right in the center

00:12:46.770 --> 00:12:48.401
is probably a sweet spot.

00:12:48.401 --> 00:12:50.400
Unfortunately, as you're
approaching the center,

00:12:50.400 --> 00:12:52.196
if you don't hit that
sweet spot exactly,

00:12:52.196 --> 00:12:54.570
it can feel very phony and
contrived on the way in there,

00:12:54.570 --> 00:12:56.480
we discovered.

00:12:56.480 --> 00:12:59.019
And then the other
big continuum is

00:12:59.019 --> 00:13:00.560
between permissive
and authoritarian.

00:13:00.560 --> 00:13:02.120
This is more about
parenting styles.

00:13:02.120 --> 00:13:04.578
So in the world of parenting,
as any of you who are parents

00:13:04.578 --> 00:13:07.160
know, probably, the
three parenting styles

00:13:07.160 --> 00:13:09.120
that you hear people talk
about are permissive,

00:13:09.120 --> 00:13:11.690
where you let your kids
do whatever they want,

00:13:11.690 --> 00:13:13.660
authoritarian, where
you're authoritarian

00:13:13.660 --> 00:13:14.900
and you're cracking the whip.

00:13:14.900 --> 00:13:17.440
And then authoritative is
the sort of in-between place

00:13:17.440 --> 00:13:19.931
where you're not letting
your kids run wild,

00:13:19.931 --> 00:13:21.430
you're not cracking
the whip, you're

00:13:21.430 --> 00:13:24.070
trying to find a balance
between those two things.

00:13:24.070 --> 00:13:25.630
And again, there's
a lot of books

00:13:25.630 --> 00:13:27.390
that are about sort of--
because there was kind

00:13:27.390 --> 00:13:29.060
of a backlash going on at that
time against overparenting

00:13:29.060 --> 00:13:31.207
and helicopter parenting,
quite a lot of books that

00:13:31.207 --> 00:13:32.540
were sort of anti-authoritarian.

00:13:35.269 --> 00:13:37.060
And there was a lot of
books that are very,

00:13:37.060 --> 00:13:41.350
like, these old boy scientist
books that were getting

00:13:41.350 --> 00:13:43.630
reissued and stuff that
are sort of, here's

00:13:43.630 --> 00:13:44.640
how to do cool
projects but you have

00:13:44.640 --> 00:13:45.889
to follow these rules exactly.

00:13:45.889 --> 00:13:47.511
There's no room for wiggle room.

00:13:47.511 --> 00:13:50.010
And there are some books in the
middle like "Make" magazine,

00:13:50.010 --> 00:13:51.850
"DIY Kids," that
we felt were sort

00:13:51.850 --> 00:13:54.702
of hitting that sweet spot
between the two, where it's fun

00:13:54.702 --> 00:13:56.410
and you can kind of--
there's guidelines,

00:13:56.410 --> 00:13:58.160
but you don't have to
follow them exactly,

00:13:58.160 --> 00:14:01.050
and there's room for
experimentation and play.

00:14:01.050 --> 00:14:04.570
So in my world, I put the two
codes, two binary opposites

00:14:04.570 --> 00:14:06.790
together, and you get
a four-quadrant map.

00:14:06.790 --> 00:14:09.000
So where silly meets
authoritarian we're calling it

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:12.100
the cajoling section
on the bottom left.

00:14:12.100 --> 00:14:15.120
And these are kids'
books that were

00:14:15.120 --> 00:14:18.860
sort of fun teacher, the camp
counselor, maybe a cool cousin

00:14:18.860 --> 00:14:19.700
at best.

00:14:19.700 --> 00:14:22.390
So the green ones that are kind
of-- that are farthest out--

00:14:22.390 --> 00:14:24.810
are sort of lame category,
or extreme versions

00:14:24.810 --> 00:14:26.300
of that quadrant.

00:14:26.300 --> 00:14:28.420
The yellow codes that
you're seeing here

00:14:28.420 --> 00:14:29.500
are kind of the middle
of the row, which

00:14:29.500 --> 00:14:31.083
can seem a little
phony and contrived.

00:14:31.083 --> 00:14:33.180
And the blue ones seemed
pretty cool to us.

00:14:33.180 --> 00:14:35.080
So at best, in the
cajoling quadrant,

00:14:35.080 --> 00:14:36.455
you had like a
cool older cousin.

00:14:36.455 --> 00:14:39.290
I had cool older cousins
in the '70s who, you know,

00:14:39.290 --> 00:14:41.720
they're cooler than your
teacher or a camp counselor.

00:14:41.720 --> 00:14:43.120
They're showing you something
that's maybe kind of dangerous

00:14:43.120 --> 00:14:44.870
that parents wouldn't
let you do normally.

00:14:44.870 --> 00:14:46.142
It's exciting.

00:14:46.142 --> 00:14:48.350
But they may be getting you
out of your comfort zone,

00:14:48.350 --> 00:14:49.470
which is a good thing.

00:14:49.470 --> 00:14:51.095
TONY LEONE: One thing
we did here, too,

00:14:51.095 --> 00:14:54.720
is we assigned personas to
some of these, on the map

00:14:54.720 --> 00:14:55.420
here as well.

00:14:55.420 --> 00:14:57.015
And it helps from
a design standpoint

00:14:57.015 --> 00:14:58.640
because once we start
going into design

00:14:58.640 --> 00:15:02.430
it starts to give a sense as
to, who are we trying to target

00:15:02.430 --> 00:15:04.680
and who is it
being designed for?

00:15:04.680 --> 00:15:07.620
So to apply personas
here is a nice tool

00:15:07.620 --> 00:15:09.050
in the design process.

00:15:09.050 --> 00:15:11.550
JOSH GLENN: So in the top left
where permissive meets silly,

00:15:11.550 --> 00:15:12.790
this is the wacky quadrant.

00:15:12.790 --> 00:15:15.770
And it's quite a popular
quadrant for kids' books.

00:15:15.770 --> 00:15:18.190
We were saying the worst of
it is like the creepy uncle.

00:15:18.190 --> 00:15:19.690
A book like "Oh,
Yuck!" is something

00:15:19.690 --> 00:15:21.930
that maybe an uncle
with bad boundaries

00:15:21.930 --> 00:15:23.638
would give to your
kid, and you'd kind of

00:15:23.638 --> 00:15:26.084
be bummed out that he had
given that to your kid.

00:15:26.084 --> 00:15:27.500
Kitsch is somewhere
in the middle.

00:15:27.500 --> 00:15:28.290
And then the kooky aunt.

00:15:28.290 --> 00:15:30.623
We think that's a really good
thing, to be a kooky aunt.

00:15:30.623 --> 00:15:32.110
So that's a good
version of wacky.

00:15:32.110 --> 00:15:33.940
Then in the top right, where
permissive meets earnest.

00:15:33.940 --> 00:15:36.481
This is like sherpa parenting,
as people were calling it back

00:15:36.481 --> 00:15:37.190
then.

00:15:37.190 --> 00:15:41.060
So it's sort of hippie
parents, slacker moms, low key.

00:15:41.060 --> 00:15:43.760
And we felt like maybe there
was a white space there

00:15:43.760 --> 00:15:44.570
or something.

00:15:44.570 --> 00:15:47.440
There wasn't really a cool
version of that quadrant yet.

00:15:47.440 --> 00:15:49.606
And then authoritarian
meets earnest.

00:15:49.606 --> 00:15:51.230
We called this the
particular quadrant.

00:15:51.230 --> 00:15:54.147
This is like fussy grandparents,
helicopter parents,

00:15:54.147 --> 00:15:56.105
at best, maybe with the
grandparents, are geeky

00:15:56.105 --> 00:15:58.980
and crafty parents, like Mark
Frauenfelder from "Make" doing

00:15:58.980 --> 00:16:01.600
stuff with his daughter
sort of would fit there.

00:16:01.600 --> 00:16:03.200
So that gives us a map.

00:16:03.200 --> 00:16:06.990
Then we layered Tony's
research on top of that map,

00:16:06.990 --> 00:16:09.600
and we decided that
there was an opportunity

00:16:09.600 --> 00:16:11.520
to do something that
fit with our values

00:16:11.520 --> 00:16:13.670
as parents and as
people who wanted

00:16:13.670 --> 00:16:16.027
to do a book that was different.

00:16:16.027 --> 00:16:17.610
And it also-- there
was an opportunity

00:16:17.610 --> 00:16:19.800
that no one else was doing
something in the space.

00:16:19.800 --> 00:16:22.640
It's sort of a little more
earnest than the kooky aunt,

00:16:22.640 --> 00:16:24.619
a little more permissive,
maybe, than the geeky

00:16:24.619 --> 00:16:25.410
and crafty parents.

00:16:25.410 --> 00:16:26.540
It's a little
easier stuff to do.

00:16:26.540 --> 00:16:28.581
You don't have to follow
all these rules exactly.

00:16:30.620 --> 00:16:32.820
So it's maybe a little
bit on the serious side,

00:16:32.820 --> 00:16:35.110
but not all the way to
earnest, and a little bit

00:16:35.110 --> 00:16:38.290
on the permissive side, but
sort of fun authoritative,

00:16:38.290 --> 00:16:39.915
but not all the way
towards permissive.

00:16:42.620 --> 00:16:46.400
So we decided to take our
inspiration from the books that

00:16:46.400 --> 00:16:49.744
were kind of right
around that area.

00:16:49.744 --> 00:16:50.910
So this was our opportunity.

00:16:50.910 --> 00:16:52.743
This was all-- we're
making it sound like we

00:16:52.743 --> 00:16:55.639
did this kind of like
creepy adult coming in

00:16:55.639 --> 00:16:57.680
from the outside and
studying the kids' category.

00:16:57.680 --> 00:17:01.800
But it was also-- the idea was
to try to articulate and put

00:17:01.800 --> 00:17:04.940
language and visuals to our
own parenting philosophy

00:17:04.940 --> 00:17:07.099
and what we wanted
this book to be.

00:17:07.099 --> 00:17:08.890
So then the design
codes we mapped on here.

00:17:08.890 --> 00:17:10.300
Do you want to talk
about this, Tony?

00:17:10.300 --> 00:17:11.008
TONY LEONE: Sure.

00:17:11.008 --> 00:17:13.750
Here what we're
able to do is, as we

00:17:13.750 --> 00:17:16.405
mapped the imagery,
images of the books

00:17:16.405 --> 00:17:17.780
from my research
on here, we were

00:17:17.780 --> 00:17:21.869
able to take the themes
that emerged and map

00:17:21.869 --> 00:17:24.960
the themes on here as well, just
to help further articulate it.

00:17:24.960 --> 00:17:27.280
So around our sweet
spot, we thought maybe

00:17:27.280 --> 00:17:30.110
some contemporary
technical, certainly

00:17:30.110 --> 00:17:33.440
contemporary modern,
little bit of nostalgia,

00:17:33.440 --> 00:17:38.650
and the idea of something
being undesigned.

00:17:38.650 --> 00:17:41.740
It certainly is
designed, but it's not--

00:17:41.740 --> 00:17:44.397
there's a certain simplicity
to it that lends itself--

00:17:44.397 --> 00:17:46.730
JOSH GLENN: Our big example
of that was the "Whole Earth

00:17:46.730 --> 00:17:49.790
Catalog," like '70s stuff that
we grew up with, like the Zoom

00:17:49.790 --> 00:17:52.187
"Do" books in the '70s and
"The Whole Earth Catalog."

00:17:52.187 --> 00:17:54.020
They are designed, but
they look undesigned.

00:17:54.020 --> 00:17:56.195
They look kind of
pasted down on purpose.

00:17:58.860 --> 00:18:04.100
TONY LEONE: So from there
we went into inspiration.

00:18:04.100 --> 00:18:05.740
Where do we take
all this research?

00:18:05.740 --> 00:18:08.670
Where we take the semiotic
analysis, and what's

00:18:08.670 --> 00:18:12.220
going to inspire us visually
against all these codes?

00:18:12.220 --> 00:18:14.380
So again, it's
pretty much what I

00:18:14.380 --> 00:18:16.470
do with any large-scale
design project.

00:18:16.470 --> 00:18:18.460
So we looked at
doodle-like-- we want

00:18:18.460 --> 00:18:20.677
the doodle-like
illustration, the idea being

00:18:20.677 --> 00:18:22.510
that we would hire
professional illustrators

00:18:22.510 --> 00:18:25.200
and it would certainly be
done in a professional way,

00:18:25.200 --> 00:18:27.540
but it would have a much
more approachable look,

00:18:27.540 --> 00:18:30.030
almost as if a kid
could have drawn it.

00:18:30.030 --> 00:18:32.560
My son can't draw anything
quite as cool as this,

00:18:32.560 --> 00:18:36.060
but he could certainly
aspire to it.

00:18:36.060 --> 00:18:38.320
Certainly the idea of
scrapbooks and collages.

00:18:38.320 --> 00:18:40.750
These are just images I
found around the Internet

00:18:40.750 --> 00:18:43.880
and through research of just
something that might inspire

00:18:43.880 --> 00:18:47.150
color or a juxtaposition
of imagery.

00:18:47.150 --> 00:18:51.910
Certainly hand-drawn
typographic textures

00:18:51.910 --> 00:18:55.000
with the idea of
a DIY, something

00:18:55.000 --> 00:18:57.320
that had the maker's
hand involved

00:18:57.320 --> 00:19:00.130
in some of the
typography might be nice.

00:19:00.130 --> 00:19:03.170
Cool books, DIY feel, and
again, the creator's hand.

00:19:03.170 --> 00:19:04.850
So this really
started to lead us

00:19:04.850 --> 00:19:07.050
down a trail of what we
wanted our illustration

00:19:07.050 --> 00:19:07.850
style to look like.

00:19:07.850 --> 00:19:10.510
If you remember, in the
first spreads we put together

00:19:10.510 --> 00:19:13.480
for the pitch, it had a very
technical sort of feel to it.

00:19:13.480 --> 00:19:16.340
But after our research
in the semiotic analysis,

00:19:16.340 --> 00:19:19.560
we decided we wanted something
very much with a hand quality

00:19:19.560 --> 00:19:21.220
feel to it.

00:19:21.220 --> 00:19:23.200
So that led us to two
illustrators, the first

00:19:23.200 --> 00:19:24.880
being Mister Reusch.

00:19:24.880 --> 00:19:27.300
His actual name is Mark Reusch,
but his illustration name

00:19:27.300 --> 00:19:28.741
is Mister Reusch.

00:19:28.741 --> 00:19:30.740
The interesting thing
about the two illustrators

00:19:30.740 --> 00:19:32.920
we brought on to the
project is neither of them

00:19:32.920 --> 00:19:35.210
have the style that you
currently see in the book.

00:19:35.210 --> 00:19:40.820
So Mark's style, it's very
hand-drawn but very painterly.

00:19:40.820 --> 00:19:43.190
He tends to paint a
lot of his work, even

00:19:43.190 --> 00:19:45.902
his black and white
work at the bottom.

00:19:45.902 --> 00:19:47.360
JOSH GLENN: He's
done a lot of work

00:19:47.360 --> 00:19:48.730
for video games, snowboards.

00:19:48.730 --> 00:19:49.110
TONY LEONE: Yeah.

00:19:49.110 --> 00:19:50.902
Burton Snowboards--
JOSH GLENN: Rock Band.

00:19:50.902 --> 00:19:52.090
TONY LEONE: --shoes.

00:19:52.090 --> 00:19:54.090
I think he's done a little
bit of work for Nike.

00:19:54.090 --> 00:19:55.740
But it's very painterly style.

00:19:55.740 --> 00:19:57.900
So he's someone I
know personally,

00:19:57.900 --> 00:20:01.000
so I asked him if-- can you
do something more sketchy.

00:20:01.000 --> 00:20:04.540
So we gave each of the
illustrators an assignment

00:20:04.540 --> 00:20:08.080
and it was like, draw some
objects, musical instruments,

00:20:08.080 --> 00:20:09.056
sewing supplies.

00:20:09.056 --> 00:20:10.430
We knew some of
these things were

00:20:10.430 --> 00:20:11.846
going to be appearing
in the book,

00:20:11.846 --> 00:20:14.450
sewing supplies and
camping equipment.

00:20:14.450 --> 00:20:15.940
So Mark did a great job.

00:20:15.940 --> 00:20:18.921
JOSH GLENN: And poor Mark had
just broken his wrist sledding

00:20:18.921 --> 00:20:20.670
right when Tony was
asking him to do this,

00:20:20.670 --> 00:20:21.870
and he didn't want to tell us.

00:20:21.870 --> 00:20:22.500
TONY LEONE: Yeah,
he didn't tell us

00:20:22.500 --> 00:20:24.124
he had broken his
right hand, and so he

00:20:24.124 --> 00:20:25.610
drew all these
with his left hand.

00:20:25.610 --> 00:20:27.329
And he drew them
really big because he

00:20:27.329 --> 00:20:29.120
could have more control
with his left hand,

00:20:29.120 --> 00:20:30.780
and he scanned them
and shrunk them.

00:20:30.780 --> 00:20:32.610
JOSH GLENN: And he didn't tell
us until like a year later.

00:20:32.610 --> 00:20:32.649
TONY LEONE: Yeah.

00:20:32.649 --> 00:20:34.232
We didn't find out
until a year later.

00:20:34.232 --> 00:20:35.710
He really wanted the project.

00:20:35.710 --> 00:20:37.930
Heather is another-- we all
knew each other from back

00:20:37.930 --> 00:20:38.846
in the Mass Arts days.

00:20:38.846 --> 00:20:42.050
I do want to say I didn't
just go to my friends

00:20:42.050 --> 00:20:42.820
for this project.

00:20:42.820 --> 00:20:45.370
We actually did
research, and I contacted

00:20:45.370 --> 00:20:47.920
some pretty well-known
illustrators in New York.

00:20:47.920 --> 00:20:50.725
And after looking at these
other illustrators' work

00:20:50.725 --> 00:20:52.100
I was like, I
really think people

00:20:52.100 --> 00:20:54.380
I know can actually do
what we're looking for.

00:20:54.380 --> 00:20:56.950
So that's why I said we more
or less gave them a test.

00:20:56.950 --> 00:21:00.950
Heather's more of a fine
artist and an art educator.

00:21:00.950 --> 00:21:04.990
She teaches art in the
Springfield, Mass high school

00:21:04.990 --> 00:21:05.750
system.

00:21:05.750 --> 00:21:08.220
But she-- I knew her
from back at Mass Art.

00:21:08.220 --> 00:21:11.750
I knew she could do
what we're looking for.

00:21:11.750 --> 00:21:13.650
So these are some
of her sketchbooks.

00:21:13.650 --> 00:21:16.800
These are some-- she does
these beautiful giant cut-paper

00:21:16.800 --> 00:21:20.602
illustrations that are
more or less installations.

00:21:20.602 --> 00:21:22.310
This is some of her
black and white work.

00:21:22.310 --> 00:21:25.180
We gave her the same test,
so she drew some camping

00:21:25.180 --> 00:21:28.950
equipment, some sewing
supplies, and she drew actually

