We're going to do
another one on adventure.

00:26:00.991 --> 00:26:02.250
We're not sure after that.

00:26:02.250 --> 00:26:04.700
So in spirit of the
games book, does anyone

00:26:04.700 --> 00:26:05.951
want to play one of our games?

00:26:05.951 --> 00:26:07.575
Let's play a little
game while we still

00:26:07.575 --> 00:26:08.830
have a few more minutes.

00:26:08.830 --> 00:26:11.590
It's a-- I'm like
Jane McGonigal.

00:26:11.590 --> 00:26:12.770
I make everyone play a game.

00:26:15.940 --> 00:26:22.310
It's a low-tech parlor game
called Telephone Pictionary.

00:26:22.310 --> 00:26:24.331
So it's like the
game Telephone, where

00:26:24.331 --> 00:26:26.830
as you whisper a word to someone
and it goes along the line,

00:26:26.830 --> 00:26:29.080
it gets more and more-- it
gets farther and farther

00:26:29.080 --> 00:26:30.162
away for what it started.

00:26:30.162 --> 00:26:31.870
And it's like Pictionary,
in which you're

00:26:31.870 --> 00:26:33.482
drawing a picture of something
that someone else is trying

00:26:33.482 --> 00:26:35.357
to communicate to you,
but you may not always

00:26:35.357 --> 00:26:36.730
know exactly what that is.

00:26:36.730 --> 00:26:45.120
So the way this game works
is that the first person

00:26:45.120 --> 00:26:47.610
will write a sentence here,
or some kind of phrase.

00:26:47.610 --> 00:26:51.790
It could be like, the
cat walked on the moon.

00:26:51.790 --> 00:26:53.870
Grandma was roller skating.

00:26:53.870 --> 00:26:55.480
Just something like that.

00:26:55.480 --> 00:26:57.950
You hand that pad
to somebody else.

00:26:57.950 --> 00:27:03.600
They turn the page and they draw
a picture of what you said, OK?

00:27:03.600 --> 00:27:05.560
So it's a sentence
and then a picture.

00:27:05.560 --> 00:27:07.987
You then hand the
picture to somebody else.

00:27:07.987 --> 00:27:09.820
They don't know what
the first sentence was.

00:27:09.820 --> 00:27:11.430
All they can see
is your picture.

00:27:11.430 --> 00:27:13.910
So they then turn the
page and write a sentence

00:27:13.910 --> 00:27:16.160
based on what they think the
picture is, and so forth.

00:27:16.160 --> 00:27:18.632
So when you get handed a pad,
if it's got a sentence here,

00:27:18.632 --> 00:27:19.340
you do a picture.

00:27:19.340 --> 00:27:21.610
If it's got a picture
here, you do a sentence.

00:27:21.610 --> 00:27:24.290
And the first person who gets
the pad has to write a phrase.

00:27:24.290 --> 00:27:26.550
Any questions?

00:27:26.550 --> 00:27:28.828
All right, I'm going to pass
out three different ones.

00:27:28.828 --> 00:27:29.676
TONY LEONE: Josh, I
can pass them this way.

00:27:29.676 --> 00:27:31.120
JOSH GLENN: OK.

00:27:31.120 --> 00:27:32.495
TONY LEONE: Do
you have a marker?

00:27:34.612 --> 00:27:35.820
JOSH GLENN: You get to start.

00:27:39.150 --> 00:27:41.880
TONY LEONE: You want to go?

00:27:41.880 --> 00:27:43.450
JOSH GLENN: All right.

00:27:43.450 --> 00:27:45.660
Parlor games-- while
you guys are starting,

00:27:45.660 --> 00:27:46.700
I'll talk a little
bit about the game.

00:27:46.700 --> 00:27:48.158
TONY LEONE: Starts
with a sentence,

00:27:48.158 --> 00:27:50.137
some sort of statement.

00:27:50.137 --> 00:27:52.220
JOSH GLENN: Yeah, so some
kind of evocative phrase

00:27:52.220 --> 00:27:57.220
or sentence, short, that can
get someone to draw a picture.

00:27:57.220 --> 00:28:00.470
So the games book picks up
on some of the-- obviously

00:28:00.470 --> 00:28:02.630
looks a lot like
the "Unbored" book,

00:28:02.630 --> 00:28:05.190
and it picks up on some of
the same kind of rubrics

00:28:05.190 --> 00:28:05.940
that we developed.

00:28:05.940 --> 00:28:08.710
Like we have Best Ever lists,
like our favorite novels,

00:28:08.710 --> 00:28:10.089
our favorite board games.

00:28:10.089 --> 00:28:12.130
For this one we have so
many favorite board games

00:28:12.130 --> 00:28:14.420
we broke it into favorite
cooperative board

00:28:14.420 --> 00:28:17.690
games, favorite quick board
games, favorite reboots

00:28:17.690 --> 00:28:19.860
of board games.

00:28:19.860 --> 00:28:22.600
We have a lot of-- I think
maybe 75 or 80 game instructions

00:28:22.600 --> 00:28:23.220
in here.

00:28:23.220 --> 00:28:25.080
And again, we try not
to be too instructive,

00:28:25.080 --> 00:28:26.950
so we sort of give guidelines
for how to play the game.

00:28:26.950 --> 00:28:28.950
And then we really
encourage-- we usually

00:28:28.950 --> 00:28:31.240
have a little sidebar that
has some hacks of the game,

00:28:31.240 --> 00:28:33.240
and then we encourage the
kids and their parents

00:28:33.240 --> 00:28:35.950
to invent their own
hacks for the games.

00:28:35.950 --> 00:28:42.400
And we have comics that tell
the history of various things.

00:28:42.400 --> 00:28:45.870
So here's a history of
board games told in comics.

00:28:45.870 --> 00:28:48.440
We have how to, sort of
"Make" magazine-style how

00:28:48.440 --> 00:28:54.300
to articles with photos.

00:28:54.300 --> 00:28:57.290
So there's just so much
in these little books.

00:28:57.290 --> 00:28:59.270
And I think it took
us like a year to do.

00:28:59.270 --> 00:29:02.500
Here's a duct tape, a
game out of duck tape.

00:29:02.500 --> 00:29:05.941
Here's a rocket-launching game
that my brother-in-law, who

00:29:05.941 --> 00:29:07.690
teaches math in the
Boston public schools,

00:29:07.690 --> 00:29:11.590
uses to teach angles.

00:29:11.590 --> 00:29:13.690
They have to make a very
dangerous, actually,

00:29:13.690 --> 00:29:16.101
launch out of PVC
pipe, which we thought

00:29:16.101 --> 00:29:18.600
was safe because he had a book
from NASA about how to do it.

00:29:18.600 --> 00:29:19.780
But after this book
came out we realized

00:29:19.780 --> 00:29:21.154
that NASA has
recalled that book.

00:29:26.046 --> 00:29:30.340
Geo games, you know,
GPS-type games, geocaching.

00:29:30.340 --> 00:29:34.220
I think there's even a Google
Earth game section in here.

00:29:34.220 --> 00:29:37.860
So one thing we like
about parlor games, which

00:29:37.860 --> 00:29:39.740
is the game that we're
passing around now,

00:29:39.740 --> 00:29:44.880
is that parlor games just
inherently brings the family

00:29:44.880 --> 00:29:47.550
together because you're all
facing each other in a circle.

00:29:47.550 --> 00:29:49.370
You're not distracted
by any screens.

00:29:49.370 --> 00:29:52.240
You're not even
looking at a board.

00:29:52.240 --> 00:29:54.527
Oftentimes there's
no equipment at all,

00:29:54.527 --> 00:29:56.360
or maybe just a pencil
and a piece of paper.

00:29:56.360 --> 00:29:59.500
There's a bunch in here that
our families like to play.

00:29:59.500 --> 00:30:03.090
And the nice thing
about family game night

00:30:03.090 --> 00:30:06.490
is that it's just an
amazing way for a family

00:30:06.490 --> 00:30:07.950
to affirm they all
like each other,

00:30:07.950 --> 00:30:10.199
because you don't have to
do it, you know what I mean?

00:30:10.199 --> 00:30:12.470
There's no reason to
do a family game night.

00:30:12.470 --> 00:30:14.170
It's not helpful,
it's not productive,

00:30:14.170 --> 00:30:17.250
it's not doing chores,
not creating something.

00:30:17.250 --> 00:30:20.450
It's just having fun
together on a school night.

00:30:20.450 --> 00:30:22.414
And that's really
nice, actually.

00:30:22.414 --> 00:30:25.080
It's a nice little break to have
with your family once in awhile

00:30:25.080 --> 00:30:26.680
to make that happen.

00:30:26.680 --> 00:30:32.726
How are we doing on the pads?

00:30:32.726 --> 00:30:33.226
All right.

00:30:33.226 --> 00:30:35.394
Let's let them go
a little farther.

00:30:35.394 --> 00:30:37.810
TONY LEONE: One thing I just
wanted to add about our books

00:30:37.810 --> 00:30:40.890
as well is that Josh and I
both came out of the zine world

00:30:40.890 --> 00:30:42.570
from the '90s.

00:30:42.570 --> 00:30:45.440
I worked on a punk
zine in the early '90s,

00:30:45.440 --> 00:30:47.650
and we're both out of
the punk and hardcore

00:30:47.650 --> 00:30:48.850
scene from the '80s.

00:30:48.850 --> 00:30:50.850
So our book, from
the beginning, we

00:30:50.850 --> 00:30:53.260
wanted it to have this sort
of eclectic feel, where

00:30:53.260 --> 00:30:54.800
it has excerpts from old books.

00:30:54.800 --> 00:30:59.020
And as Josh was saying, it's got
game theory, game activities.

00:30:59.020 --> 00:31:01.720
So it was designed
to be simple enough

00:31:01.720 --> 00:31:06.072
to incorporate all of these sort
of divergent pieces of content.

00:31:06.072 --> 00:31:06.780
JOSH GLENN: Yeah.

00:31:06.780 --> 00:31:10.130
It ended up being actually quite
complex sort of structurally,

00:31:10.130 --> 00:31:14.476
the book, because it's--
and the way Tony finally--

00:31:14.476 --> 00:31:17.850
on the first book, as we finally
got to the end of the finish

00:31:17.850 --> 00:31:20.526
line there, was the idea ended
up being kind of, it's supposed

00:31:20.526 --> 00:31:23.790
to look like an old-fashioned
manual of how to do stuff.

00:31:23.790 --> 00:31:26.635
But then somebody's hacked
it by scribbling notes on it.

00:31:26.635 --> 00:31:28.010
TONY LEONE: Sort
of redrawing it.

00:31:28.010 --> 00:31:29.051
JOSH GLENN: Redrawing it.

00:31:29.051 --> 00:31:30.780
And crossing things
out, and ripping

00:31:30.780 --> 00:31:32.200
things out of other pages
and sticking them in

00:31:32.200 --> 00:31:34.390
like you might do with a
cookbook, like recipes.

00:31:34.390 --> 00:31:36.264
So there's a lot of
things that look taped in

00:31:36.264 --> 00:31:39.026
or that are done on torn
paper or graph paper.

00:31:39.026 --> 00:31:41.650
TONY LEONE: Yeah, there's a lot
of torn paper texture in there.

00:31:41.650 --> 00:31:42.320
JOSH GLENN: So
yeah, we're hoping

00:31:42.320 --> 00:31:44.260
at sort of a subliminal
level, again,

00:31:44.260 --> 00:31:46.960
kids'll get the
idea that what we're

00:31:46.960 --> 00:31:48.460
trying to teach
with these books is

00:31:48.460 --> 00:31:50.560
DIY, the same thing
that Tony and I did back

00:31:50.560 --> 00:31:51.560
when we met in the '90s.

00:31:51.560 --> 00:31:55.170
Like doing it yourself is much
more fun than buying something

00:31:55.170 --> 00:31:57.030
that's already made for you.

00:31:57.030 --> 00:32:01.590
And even if it doesn't look
as good or perfect as the sort

00:32:01.590 --> 00:32:03.841
